    "sections": [
      {
        "chapter_number": "",
        "chapter_title": "Introduction",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "paragraph_number": "1.1",
            "summary": "This supervisory statement is relevant to Bank Recovery and Resolution Directive (BRRD) undertakings1 to which the Contractual Recognition Part of the PRA Rulebook applies,2 hereafter referred to as ‘",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          },
          {
            "paragraph_number": "1.2",
            "summary": "The supervisory statement sets out the PRA’s expectations on BRRD firms with regard to impracticability in the context of the contractual recognition requirement. The statement sets out the considerat",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          },
          {
            "paragraph_number": "1.3",
            "summary": "Providing clarity on the PRA’s expectations in this area supports the PRA’s general objective of promoting safety and soundness of firms by reducing the adverse effect that the disorderly failure of a",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "chapter_number": "",
        "chapter_title": "Determining impracticability",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "paragraph_number": "2.1",
            "summary": "The PRA expects BRRD firms to make their own reasoned assessment with regard to impracticability in relation to phase 2 liabilities (ie unsecured liabilities in scope of the Contractual Recognition of",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          },
          {
            "paragraph_number": "2.2",
            "summary": "BRRD firms could, for instance, take the view that the inclusion of contractual recognition language is impracticable if:",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          },
          {
            "paragraph_number": "2.3",
            "summary": "The above reasons for invoking impracticability are not exhaustive but provide examples of the considerations that could lead to a determination of impracticability.",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          },
          {
            "paragraph_number": "2.4",
            "summary": "The PRA does not consider loss of competitiveness or profitability to be grounds for an impracticability judgment, as this is not in line with the policy intent of the contractual recognition requirem",
            "as_at_date": "01/08/2016"
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
